Wash and dry all produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%units}, separating
whites from greens. Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat.
Add scallion whites and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.
Stir in @jasmine rice{3/4%cup}, 1¼ cups water, and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.
Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is
tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Dice @roma tomato{1%unit}. Zest and quarter @lime{1%unit}. In a #small bowl{},
combine tomato, scallion greens, a squeeze of lime juice, and half the lime
zest. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Slice @jalapeño{1%unit} into thin rounds, removing ribs and seeds for less
heat. In a second small bowl, combine jalapeño, 1 TBSP hot water,
@?sugar{1/2%tsp}, juice from half the lime, and a pinch of salt.

In a third small bowl, combine @guacamole{4%tbsp}, @sour cream{2%tbsp},
and a squeeze of lime juice.

Pat @diced steak{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}; season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over
high heat. Once oil is shimmering, add steak and sprinkle with
@southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned
and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Lower heat if steak begins to brown too quickly.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in remaining lime zest and season with salt.
Divide between #bowls{}. Top rice with diced steak, salsa, avocado crema,
as much pickled jalapeño as you like, and @monterey jack cheese{1/4%cup}.
Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.